ts practices is a broader theoretical argument, which Abbott uses to redefine social objects as a sequence of interconnected events rather than as fixed entities. Abbott's theories grow directly out of the Chicago School's insistence that social life be located in time and place, a tradition that has been at the heart of the school since its founding one hundred years ago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChicago School of Sociology. 0aChicago school of sociologyxHistory. 0aSchools of sociologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSociologyzIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 0aSociologyzUnited StatesvPeriodicalsxHistory. 0aSociologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asociology, sociologist, sociological, academic, scholarly, research, disciplines, departments, scholarship, modern, contemporary, science, school, rules, structures, daily life, academia, college, university, higher ed, editing, journals, articles, writing, inquiry, intellectual, rivalry, chicago, america, american, united states, usa, midwest, city, urban, illinois, periodicals, historiography, tradition.1 aGaziano, Emanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226222738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226222738/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles